Jan Dziuba

Dataset¶

I chose the MagicTelescope dataset.
Dataset is used for classification of high energy gamma particles in a ground-based atmospheric Cherenkov gamma telescope using the imaging technique.
For more detailed description check
https://www.openml.org/search?type=data&sort=runs&id=1120&status=active

Dataset contains 10 features and 19020 samples.
Classes are imbalanced with 1.8438995215311005 ratio.

  1. Find any two observations in the dataset, such that they have different variables of the highest importance, e.g. age and gender have the highest (absolute) attribution for observation A, but race and class are more important for observation B.

  1. (If possible) Select one variable X and find two observations in the dataset such that for one observation, X has a positive attribution, and for the other observation, X has a negative attribution.

In obs 0 fAlpha has big positive attribution, but in obs 3 it has big negative attribution.
fAlpha is angle of major axis with vector to origin.
We can see that in obs 0 it is significantly bigger than in obs 3.

  1. (How) Do the results differ across the two packages selected in point (3)?

     There are differences between dalex and shap, but in general order of variable importance and variable attribution sign match in both packages.  
 Exceptions are for example fconc1 in the first sample (attribution signs don't match) and fsample in the second sample (dalex considers it more important)
  1. (Using one explanation package of choice) Train another model of any class: neural network, linear model, decision tree etc. and find an observation for which SHAP attributions are different between this model and the one trained in point (1).

Task B.¶

Using shapley values formula for subsets

$${\displaystyle \phi _{j}(v)=\sum _{S\subseteq \mathcal{P}/ \{j\}}{\frac {|S|!\;\left(|\mathcal{P}|-|S|-1\right)!}{|\mathcal{P}|!}}\left(v(S\cup \{j\})-v(S)\right)}$$

Subsets of P not containing a are $\{\emptyset, \{B\}, \{C\}, \{B, C\}\}$

1* $\emptyset$ $$\frac{0!\cdot 2!}{3!}\left(v(A)-v(\emptyset)\right)=\frac{2}{6}\left(20-0\right) = \frac{20}{3}$$

2* $\{B\}$ $$\frac{1!\cdot 1!}{3!}\left(v(A,B)-v(B\right)=\frac{1}{6}\left(60-20\right) = \frac{20}{3}$$

3* $\{C\}$ $$\frac{1!\cdot 1!}{3!}\left(v(A,C)-v(C\right)=\frac{1}{6}\left(70-60\right) = \frac{10}{6}$$

4* $\{B, C\}$ $$\frac{2!\cdot 0!}{3!}\left(v(A,B,C)-v(B,C\right)=\frac{2}{6}\left(100-70\right) = 10$$

Shapley value of player A $=\tfrac{20}{3}+\tfrac{20}{3}+\tfrac{10}{6}+10=25$

In [94]:
def evaluate_model(model, X_test, Y_test):
    pred = model.predict(X_test)
    pred_proba = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

    accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_test, pred)
    precision = precision_score(Y_test, pred)
    recall = recall_score(Y_test, pred)
    auc = roc_auc_score(Y_test, pred_proba)
    f1 = f1_score(Y_test, pred)

    print('Accuracy: {}'.format(accuracy))
    print('Precision: {}'.format(precision))
    print('Recall: {}'.format(recall))
    print('AUC: {}'.format(auc))
    print('F1: {}'.format(f1))
